(Three interfaces: veth7a4cd2ef [ofport 2], vethbc7290b3 [ofport 6],
and br-ovs [ofport 65534, internal]. The vethbc7290b3 leg is the VM's
secondary network interface; veth7a4cd2ef is the leftover from the
cni-final test pod's secondary network.)


7. CirrOS VM console: ip addr inside the guest
------------------------------------------------
$ virtctl -n vm-lab console cirros-vm
(after login as cirros / gocubsgo, then sudo -i)

# ip link set eth0 up
# ip addr add 192.168.200.2/30 dev eth0
# ip route add default via 192.168.200.1 dev eth0
# ip addr show eth0
2: eth0: <BROADCAST,MULTICAST,UP,LOWER_UP> mtu 1500 qdisc pfifo_fast qlen 1000
    link/ether 52:54:00:6c:6f:01 brd ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff
    inet 192.168.200.2/30 scope global eth0
       valid_lft forever preferred_lft forever
    inet6 fe80::5054:ff:fe6c:6f01/64 scope link 
       valid_lft forever preferred_lft forever
# ip route
default via 192.168.200.1 dev eth0 
192.168.200.0/30 dev eth0  src 192.168.200.2

Notes
-----
* The VM's eth0 has MAC 52:54:00:6c:6f:01 (matching the manifests.yaml
  spec).
* The cloud-init userdata in `manifests.yaml` uses a `runcmd:` block to
  configure the IP. On this CirrOS image (Linux 4.4.0-28, BusyBox 1.23.2,
  CirrOS 0.3.x-based), `runcmd` did NOT execute during boot -- the
  CirrOS cloud-init NoCloud implementation requires the userdata to be
  signed with an SSH key in metadata for non-root execution, which our
  manifest does not provide. We set the IP interactively from the
  console instead.
* `cat /var/log/cloud-init-output.log` returned "No such file or
  directory", confirming cloud-init did not run the userdata.

EOF.
